				\begin{document}$$N_{\text{D}} = \frac{2}{{e\varepsilon \varepsilon_{0} m^{\prime}}}$$\end{document}where ND is the charge carrier density, e is the elementary electron charge (e = 1.6 × 10−19 C), ε is the dielectric constant (ε = 48), ε0 is the permittivity in vacuum (ε0 = 8.85 × 10−12 F m−1), and m is the slope of the 1/C2 versus potential plot. A charge carrier density of 2.9 × 1018 cm−3 was determined for the TiO2 NTs, but was 2.1 × 1019 cm−3 for the TiO2(N2) NTs. These results indicated that the charge carrier concentration of the TiO2 NTs was indeed increased after calcination in the non-oxidizing atmospheres. The higher defect density of the nitrogen-annealed sample also involved a higher electrical conductivity [32] and rapid charge transfer.Fig. 8
